  "summary": "Frankie learns from Mrs. Baskington-French that the young boy, Tommy, recently recovered from a fall caused by a rotten tree branch. During tea and dinner, Frankie observes Henry Baskington-French, noting his erratic and unsettling behavior. He oscillates between nervous twitching, dazed states, and sharp, sarcastic outbursts, only to appear unnaturally brilliant and rejuvenated during dinner. Frankie notices his peculiar, frightening eyes and suspects he may be an addict, though she initially doubts his involvement in the murder of Alexander Prichard because his brother was in Machabert when the crime occurred.\n\nThe following afternoon, Roger Baskington-French arrives for tea. A tall, thin man with deep blue eyes, Roger brings a Hornby train for Tommy. Frankie finds Roger likable, which leads her to conclude that her and Bobby's initial theory—that Roger pushed Prichard off the cliff—is incorrect. However, she remains uncertain about the identity of the murderer and the source of the morphine used to spike Bobby's beer.\n\nThe next day, while playing tennis, Roger confides in Frankie that he is certain Henry is using morphine to treat insomnia. Roger observes that Henry's pupils are as small as needle tips and notes that Henry becomes neurotic when his supply is low, only to transform after receiving a six o'clock parcel. Roger admits he is sharing this information because he does not know how to face Sylvia. Frankie reflects on the possibility of a drug smuggling gang but remains wary, reminding herself that charming individuals can also be murderers.",
